The powerlifting competition at the Tokyo 2020 Paralympic Games consists of 20 medal events:
A total of 180 athletes may take part in the powerlifting competition. This figure comprises 80 male and 80 female athletes, plus 20 bipartite commission places.

All athletes have three attempts to record their heaviest lift successfully against the others in their bodyweight category. Lifters complete each round in the order of the lowest lift weight requested to the highest, and when the requested lift weight is the same, by the order of the lowest lot draw.

All athletes have two minutes to start their lift from the time their name is called by the official speaker. In the third round, two weight changes are allowed. Athletes can take the bar from the rack themselves or with assistance from the chief spotter loader or the coaches.

When lifters have the bar under control, they must wait until they receive the command “start” from the chief referee. Then they must lower the bar to their chest, hold it motionless then press it upwards to arms’ length with locked elbows and hold the bar under control until the chief referee gives the rack command.

A lift attempt judged as compliant with the technical lift sequences requires the decision approval by at least two of the three referees. This is signified by the white icon on the attempt board. Three referees judge the lift; two or more white lights are needed for a good lift and two or more red lights for a no lift.

Chosen weights must be in multiples of one kilogram unless the lift is a record attempt, which may be broken by 0.5kg. To set a record, a lift must exceed the previous record by a minimum of 0.5kg. Where a world record is set during the three lifts of competition, the 0.5kg does not count towards the competition total and is rounded down to the full one kg.
If an athlete is close to breaking a record, a power lift (fourth attempt) is allowed. This is only for record purposes and does not count as the final result.

The weigh-in is the official process to verify the athletes’ final bodyweight to confirm that the athletes are within the necessary parameters permitting them to compete within their selected bodyweight categories. During the weigh-in, the athletes or their coaches must declare a starting weight and rack height.
The powerlifting competition will be held in accordance with the editions of the following documents that are in force at the time of the Games:
The official 2018-2021 World Para Powerlifting Rules and Regulations (available at https://www.paralympic.org/powerlifting/rules)

World Para Powerlifting (WPPO), working with the Tokyo 2020 competition management, will be responsible for the technical control and direction of the powerlifting competition at the Tokyo 2020 Paralympic Games.
DIFFERENCES BETWEEN THE WORLD CHAMPIONSHIPS AND THE PARALYMPIC GAMES

At world championships (WCH), each National Paralympic Committee (NPC) may enter up to 10 athletes for the women’s competition and another 10 for the men’s competition, but there must not be more than two athletes from any country in the same bodyweight category.

In the WCH, more than 400 athletes from over 70 NPCs compete and there is an extra medal event (mixed team event). At the Paralympic Games, 16 athletes per NPC (eight men and eight women) may receive a direct qualification slot, but only one athlete is allowed for each NPC in each bodyweight category. At the Games, 180 athletes from about 60 NPCs compete.
CHANGES SINCE THE RIO 2016 PARALYMPIC GAMES
New world para powerlifting rules have been applied since January 2018.
Twenty gender free slots shall be allocated by the WPPO and the IPC through the bipartite process, with priority given to the most competitive event.
Each medal event shall be allocated a minimum of eight athlete slots.
There is no equivalent sport for powerlifting at the Olympic Games.
